<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Characteristic Species</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Acacia</i> spp., <i>Albizia</i> <i>lophantha</i>, <i>Grevillea</i> spp. or <i>Leptospermum</i> <i>laevigatum</i> is dominant in the shrub or small tree canopy including <i>Acacia</i> <i>baileyana</i>, <i>Acacia</i> <i>cyclops</i>, <i>Acacia</i> <i>dealbata</i>, <i>Acacia</i> <i>longifolia</i>, <i>Acacia</i> <i>paradoxa</i>, <i>Acacia</i> <i>redolens</i>, <i>Acacia</i> <i>retinodes</i>, <i>Acacia</i> <i>saligna</i>, <i>Grevillea</i> <i>robusta</i> or <i>Grevillea</i> <i>rosmariniifolia</i>. </div>
</div>

        
	
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Vegetation Layers</h4>
	<div class="text">  Shrub < 5 (10) m; canopy is intermittent to continuous. Herbaceous layer is open. </div>
</div>

        
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Membership Rules</h4>
	<ul class="text">
		
		<li>A non-native shrub <i>Acacia</i> spp., <i>Albizia lophantha, Grevillea </i>spp. and/or <i>Leptospermum laevigatum</i> are together > 60% of the shrub canopy (Buck-Diaz et al. 2021, Sikes et al. 2021).</li>
		
		<li><i>Acacia cyclops </i>or other related species >75% relative cover in the tall shrub to low tree canopy (Buck-Diaz and Evens 2015, Verdone and Evens 2010).</li>
		
	</ul>
</div>

        
	
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Habitats</h4>
	<div class="text"> Coastal hillslopes, flats, and ridge tops. Soils are often sandy and alluvial. The USACE Wetland Inventory (2020 national list) recognizes <i>Grevillea robusta</i> as an UPL plant. Other spp. Are not considered. </div>
</div>

        
