<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Remarks</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Acacia</i> species belong to the family Fabaceae and are known for their yellow flowers and often have dissected leaves. Various shrubs, which are non-natives from Australia, thrive in the coastal and transverse ranges of California. The flowers of <i>Acacia</i> spp. can be pollinated by beetles, bees and wasps. Its seeds, spread by ants, birds, wind, water, or waste, can be long-lived, germinating after fires or other disturbances (Cal-IPC 2021). Cal-IPC ranks <i>A. dealbata </i> as Moderate; <i>A. baileyana, A. cyclops, A. longifolia, A. paradoxa, </i>and <i>A. saligna </i>as Watch.<br/>
 <br/>
<i>Leptospermum laevigatum</i> belongs to the family Myrtaceae and is native to Australia. This shrub or small tree has white flowers and narrow leaves. It grows in sand dunes and bluffs in the San Francisco Bay and central and south coast ranges of California. Its seeds are spread via wind, vehicles, soil movement, water and dumped garden waste (Cal-IPC 2017). The older stems are covered with shedding brown bark, and younger stems are green and smooth with silky hairs. The leaves are alternate along the stem and are attached to short and flat petioles. Its flowers bloom in late winter and spring and the fruit ripen from green to brown, becoming more woody as they mature. Cal-IPC ranks <i>L. laevigatum </i> as Watch.<br/>
 <br/>
<i>Grevillea</i> species are evergreen trees and shrubs distributed in central and southern coastal California (Calflora 2017). They are native to Australia and naturalized in California along with tropical and subtropical regions of the world (Cal-IPC 2017). They are prolific seeders with light weight seeds dispersed by wind. They can also spread via root suckers.  The seeds of <i>Grevillea</i> can initiate germination 20 days after dispersal. They drop large amounts of fruit and leaf litter that contain allelopathic substances and consequently inhibits the growth of understory native plants. It is at a high risk of becoming invasive in California. Cal-IPC ranks <i>Grevillea robusta </i>as Watch.<br/>
<br/>
Stands of <i>Acacia</i> spp., <i>Albizia lophantha, Leptospermum laevigatum, Grevillea</i> spp. or related shrubs to small trees occur sporadically in California, particularly along the coast and in the Coast Ranges. They are often near development having escaped from horticultural plantings and are sometimes naturally reproducing in the wild along the coastal hills; for example, they can invade disturbed places in coastal sage scrub and coastal prairies (Cal-IPC 2021).  More study of this type is needed. Stands dominated by tree species of <i>Acacia </i>currently fall under the <i>Eucalyptus spp. - Ailanthus altissima - Robinia pseudoacacia </i>Alliance. </div>
</div>

    
	
	
