    <div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
        <h4 class="header">Regional Status</h4>
        

        <ul class="text">
        
            <li><b>Central California Coast</b> (261Af, Ai, Ak). Various <i>Acacia </i>species, <i>Albizia lophantha </i>occur along the coast invading prairie, scrub and chaparral habitats (CCH 2022, Sikes et al. 2021).</li>
        
            <li><b>Northern California Coast</b> (263Ac, Ak-l). Various <i>Acacia </i>species, <i>Grevillea rosmarinifolia </i>and <i>Albizia lophantha </i>occur along the coast invading prairies, scrub, and chaparral habitats (Buck-Diaz et al. 2021, Cal-IPC 2021, CCH 2022).</li>
        
            <li><b>Southern California Coast</b> (261Bb-e, Bg, Bi-j). Various <i>Acacia </i>species, <i>Grevillea robusta, </i>and <i>Albizia lophantha </i>occur along the coast invading prairies, scrub, chaparral, and moist areas habitats (Buck-Diaz et al. 2015, Cal-IPC 2021, CCH 2022, VegCAMP 2007a, Verdone and Evens 2010).</li>
        
        </ul>
    </div>


    
	
<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Management Considerations</h4>
	<div class="text"> Since most of the species are on the Watch list for Cal-IPC, they have the moderate to high risk of being invasive (Cal-IPC 2021). Additionally, <i>Acacia </i>species including <i>A. dealbata </i>can change soil chemistry by fixing nitrogen, and fallen leaves may have allelopathic effects that prevent growth of native plants and may also foster other invasives to establish. Acacias are commonly planted as ornamentals and can escape, especially in disturbed places where they can spread by seed or by rhizomes.  Seeds can accumulate in the soil and germinate after fire, hot weather, or other disturbances (Cal-IPC 2021). </div>
</div>

    

    

